title: For Sale:  1943 winchester model 12
postcontent: This is a winchester 1912 made in 1943 popularly known as winchester model 12. Pump action shot gun, fires12 guage catridges. By the time World War II began, stocks of shotguns were too small to support the mobilization and new orders were placed. The well regarded Winchester Model 12 trench and riot guns were again procured with a total of more than 80,000 guns ordered by the U.S. Government by 1945, more than any other combat shotgun of the time. Collectors will notice that there was a change in the ventilated heat shield during WW II from the WW I design of six rows of holes to only 4 rows starting in 1942. This example was manufactured in the the last block of guns made in 1943. A cartouche is present(GHD) but is faint. The four-hole heat shield appears to be a replacement.

postcontent: Very interesting piece of history. Up for sale or trade is a de-banned Norinco NHM90 that started life as a pre-ban 56s Triangle 56. The rifle was caught up in customes at the beginning of the import ban in 1990 hence the birth of the post ban NHM90. The NHM90's still possessed a threaded barrel that was covered in a barrel cap and came with the hideous thumb hole stock's. This rifle has had the furniture swapped with the correct Chinese wood and the barrel cap has been removed and correct slant brake has been added with the detente pin still intact. Comes with one original Chinese flatback magazine & original Chinese sling. The rifle was a 56s built rifle and shares the 1.5mm thick receiver and heavy chrome lined barrel. title: For Sale:  Parker Bros. VH  (12ga.) 1902 Shotgun
location: Lanoka Harbor, New Jersey, United States
postcontent: Parker Bros V/VH 12ga.26" Vulcan BarrelsExtractorsV/G Wood - Has very old repair to stock but is very solidI believe this is a VH due to light engraving on plates & the extractors (not ejectors)S/N dates it to 1902Very Good condition for it's ageNice tight lock up, no play, no issuesThis gun came from an estate of an older gentleman who liked to collect, but notshoot too much.Asking $800.00 OBO.................................................................................................................Parker started production of the Grade 0 (zero) in 1869. Parker started its grade numbering system at zero to denote their lowest grade made at that time. As Parker introduced the named grades they named Grade 0 guns R, S, T, U and VH. Except for the VH which describes all Grade 0 hammerless Parkers, the other names describe Grade 0 hammer guns based on various gauge and stock configurations. It had Decarbonized Steel barrels in the beginning and later used Plain Twist, Stub Twist or Plain Steel barrels. The early grade 0 guns were back action lifter guns and evolved into the front-action lifter. In 1899 the hammerless grade 0 , the VH, was introduced and it used Vulcan steel barrels. The grade 0 was the mainstay of Parker production and the fit and finish was excellent. They have little extra finish in the way of checkering or engraving and the wood used was plain, straight grain American walnut. The engraving was a simple border around the frame. The early guns had plain metal butt plates and later ones have hard rubber dogs head butt plates. The frame, forend iron and locks were casehardened.

title: For Sale/Trade:  In honor of Women’s History Month
postcontent: In honor of Women’s History Month 2018, I give you a cool historical piece owned by a woman who lived in the early 20th century!Here is a really nice example of a rare 1905-1915 Sears, Roebuck & Company mail order catalogue “Eastern Arms Co.” .32 cal (black powder cartridge) 5-shot top break revolver manufactured at the Sears-owned Meriden Firearms Co. of Meriden, Connecticut. Very similar to the H&R and Iver Johnson Arms and Cycle works revolvers of the period, these guns were marketed largely to women for home and self-defense. I’ve always wondered how many of these pistols were owned and carried for protection by women of that period and interestingly enough, this firearm was! The inside of the grips are engraved with a really cool name: “Abiliene Hans” as well as the name of the original owner, a “C.H. Haugh”. One can only wonder what the relationship between these two might have been? The pistol is in remarkeable shape for its age. The bore is in great shape and there are only two minor issues. 1) the front sight is missing but could easily be replaced by a competent gunsmith and 2) While the main spring is in great shape, for some reason it is firing double action only and likely needs a tune up. (I didn’t want to completely dissasemble the frame to try to fix it myself). While I suspect it is an easy fix, you could always just leave it and/or bob the hammer.The gun is perfectly functional, however you DO NOT want to fire modern .32 ammunition in it under any circumstances. You would need to find black powder cowboy action loads or load your own black powder cartridges for it. I’m including a leather holster and a super cool contemporary Royal Neighbors of America medal. The Royal Neighbors of America was an early 1900s womens fraternal organization that championed women’s rights during the suggerage era, a fitting companion to the gun.Given the owners’ signatures on the grips and that one of them was female which is pretty rare and cool from a historical standpoint, I’m asking $300 firm for the pistol.
